DAY 10 - CONSTRUCTOR

Today you'll learn something every Java project uses.

Problem

Right now you write:

Student s1 = new Student();

s1.name = "Manohar";
s1.age = 24;

Every time.

Suppose you create 500 students.

You'll write

name
age

500 times.

That's boring.

Constructor Solves This

Think you buy a new phone.

When you buy it

Brand
Storage
RAM

are already set.

You don't open the phone and install RAM yourself.

Constructor works the same way.

Constructor
class Student{

    Student()
    {
        System.out.println("Object Created");
    }

}

Notice carefully.

There is

NO return type

Not even

void
Object Creation
Student s1 = new Student();

Output

Object Created

Java automatically calls the constructor.

You don't call it yourself.

Parameterized Constructor
class Student{

    String name;

    int age;

    Student(String n,int a){

        name = n;

        age = a;

    }

}

Create object

Student s1 = new Student("Manohar",24);

Print

System.out.println(s1.name);

System.out.println(s1.age);

Output

Manohar

24

Notice something?

No need to write

s1.name="Manohar";

The constructor did it.

Why Constructor?

Without constructor

Student s1 = new Student();

s1.name="Manohar";

s1.age=24;

With constructor

Student s1 = new Student("Manohar",24);

Less code.

Cleaner code.

Professional code.

